## Configuration

{% borderedPanel %}

{% collapse title="How do I configure the navigation bar links?" %}
The navigation bar is configured in the file named `project-config.ts`, at the root of your project source. If you previously switched to the "Pages" view, you will need to switch back to "Source" view to see it in the sidebar. Alternatively, you can jump to the file by hitting {% keys cmd=true char="P" /%} and type `project-config`.
```ts
export default {
  navbar: {
    topLinks: [
      { title: "Support", href: "/" },
      // ...
    ],
    tabs: [
      { title: "Home", href: "/" },
      // ...
    ],
  },
```
{% /collapse %}

{% collapse title="How do I add an entry to the guides sidebar?" %}
Similar to the navigation bar, the Guides sidebar menu in configured in `project-config.ts`, under the `sidebar` entry.

```ts
export default {
  // ...
  sidebars: {
    guides: [
      {
        title: "Getting started",
        pages: [
          {
            title: "Introduction",
            href: "/guides/getting-started/introduction",
          },
          {
            title: "Installation",
            href: "/guides/getting-started/installation",
          },
        ],
      },
      // ...
    ]
  }
  // ...
}
```

To add a new section or a new page inside an existing section, simply edit the list with the appropriate info.
{% /collapse %}

{% collapse title="How do I configure the guides gallery?" %}
Similar to the guides sidebar, the guides gallery is configured under the `guidesGallery` entry in `project-config.ts`

```ts
export default {
  // ...
  sampleGallery: {
    Develop: [
      {
        title: "Markdoc",
        // ...
      },
    ]
  }
}
```

The top level keys (`Develop`, `Databases`, `Deploy`) define the tab names. Inside each of the entries are the links to the guides, which include a title, a description, a cover image, and the path to the guide itself. You can add as many tabs and entries as you need, and the tab panel will adjust itself accordingly.
{% /collapse %}

{% collapse title="How do I change the primary color?" %}
By default, the primary color is `sky`. This can be changed in `tailwind.config.js`, located at the root of your project. Locate the `colors` entry, and change the `primary` key to either another predefined color from the [Tailwind palette](https://tailwindcss.com/docs/customizing-colors):

```js
colors: {
  primary: colors.sky,
},
```

or create your own, by specifying each of the variants explicity:

```js
colors: {
  primary: {
    50: '#e7fdff',
    100: '#cffafe',
    200: '#a5f3fc',
    300: '#67e8f9',
    400: '#22d3ee',
    500: '#06b6d4',
    600: '#0891b2',
    700: '#0e7490',
    800: '#155e75',
    900: '#164e63',
  }
},
```
{% /collapse %}

